# Daily Life and Work

![Lesson image for Daily Life and Work](../../../assets/images/daily-life.jpg)

Most people worked in agriculture and crafts. Homes, food, family ties, and local religious life reveal a society far broader than its monuments.

Most ancient Egyptians were not pharaohs, priests, or pyramid builders. They farmed, fished, baked, brewed, made cloth, shaped wood and stone, traded, raised children, and participated in neighborhood and temple life. Tomb models are valuable because they show work in miniature: a bakery or brewery can make production visible, but it is still an elite person’s decision to place that model in a tomb. Archaeologists therefore read such objects as evidence with a point of view, not as a transparent photograph of ordinary life.

Food and labor were connected to environment and status. Grain supported bread and beer; fish was widely available; meat and imported goods could mark wealth. Women’s lives were shaped by a patriarchal society, yet Egyptian legal and economic evidence shows women could own property, make contracts, inherit, and work in a range of occupations. “Daily life” should therefore not be reduced to a single household stereotype.

Source note: the World History Encyclopedia overview is a starting point, while museum objects let learners ask what kind of evidence survives and who commissioned it.

> **Further reading.** [Research source](https://www.worldhistory.org/article/933/daily-life-in-ancient-egypt/)
